Driving in high heels is dangerous!
Young people's pedal misstep accidents occur frequently (Auto Messe Web) - Yahoo! News
Violations that violate the Road Traffic Act
The number of reports of accidents caused by incorrect operation, such as pedal missteps, is increasing, but it is a big mistake to think that it is only a problem for elderly drivers.
In the number of pedal missteps by age group (2015 National Police Agency data), the most common age group was 1080cases under 24years old, exceeding 1032cases for those aged 75 and over.
Mistakes are never common among the elderly, and it is important to call attention to the same age.
Do you want to take a fashionable foot?
Do you want to be safe?
This data does not describe the ratio of men and women or the cause, but unlike the elderly, who are thought to come from the decline of the body, such as driving skills and reflexes, young people may be inadvertently distracted by other things such as music and conversation, and mistakes due to clothes etc. may be wrong.
In particular, some women choose high heels, pumps, sandals, and mules, depending on their clothes for the day, and drive them as they are.
Some people know that it is not suitable for driving, but some people think that it is troublesome to change clothes, but there are many people who drive without thinking about the possibility of danger at all and driving without vileness.
However, driving with high heels and sandals violates the Road Traffic Act.
One is "Violation of duty of safe driving" in which "the steering wheel, brake, and other operations shall be reliably operated" and "the driver must not cause an accident and harm the person."
The other is "Violation of the Compliance of the Public Safety Committee" in which the driver must comply with the matters stipulated by the prefectural public safety committee. For example, in the Miyazaki Prefectural Road Traffic Law Enforcement Bylaws, there is a sentence in Article XII: "Do not wear shoes that may interfere with the operation of the driver, or do not drive a vehicle (excluding light vehicles) by wearing shoes that may interfere with driving operations."
In each prefecture, the same is true of the purpose of considering driving with "shoots that may interfere with driving operation" as a violation, even if it is not specified as high heels.
Why is driving in high heels dangerous?
It is obvious when considering the basics of pedal operation safely.
For safe pedal operation, first fix the heel of the foot to the floor, put the foot to be perpendicular to the brake pedal, and tilt the foot to the right with the full point when stepping on the accelerator pedal.
At this time, regardless of the behavior of the car, it is important to fix it firmly so that the heel does not shake.
However, in high heels, the area where the heel is grounded to the floor is small, and it always blurs, and because the entire foot is attached to the height of the heel, the area of the foot to be grounded on the pedal is small and it is not possible to step firmly, and it is difficult to make fine adjustments.
This is thought to lead to danger.
In addition, most cars have a floor carpet, but this material is easy to catch the heel of the high heel, and the heel is caught when the heel is caught and the pedal can not be stepped on, or the high heel may be taken off due to the beat of the heel, sandwiched in the back of the pedal, and it may not be able to step on.
In addition, there are cases where the heel gets stuck in the back of the pedal when stepping on the pedal and then returns it, and the accelerator pedal can no longer return.
