The Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries on the 27th released a draft amendment to the epidemic prevention guideline that enables preventive vaccination of domestic pigs that are not currently recognized in order to prevent the spread of the spread of livestock infectious disease "pork cholera".
The policy is to select nine prefectures, including Gifu and Aichi prefectures, where infections with pigs and wild boars have been confirmed.
The movement of vaccinated live pigs and fertilized eggs is restricted in the region, but it is permitted to distribute meat and processed products outside the region.
After making public comments (opinion solicitation) to the general public, we aim to complete the procedure as early as October.
By using vaccines and allowing extraterritorial distribution such as meat, it will no longer be a "clean country" that has been certified by international organizations, and it may affect the export of pork.
Since the outbreak in September last year, Japan has been on hold for a while.
In the revised proposal, the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries has established a "vaccination recommended area" based on the opinions of experts on areas where the risk of infection from wild boars to pigs is high.
The target prefecture will create a "vaccination program" that summarizes the scope, timing, number of heads, and how to proceed, and after confirmation by the ministry, the governor will allow it to be used at the governor's discretion.
The other seven prefectures listed as recommended vaccinations are Saitama, Toyama, Ishikawa, Fukui, Nagano, Mie, and Shiga.
When the guidelines are revised, the region will assess the situation and decide again.
In principle, the movement of vaccinated pigs, semen, fertilized eggs, carcasses, excrement, etc. will be restricted to the region.
Meat and processed products will not be targeted in light of the cost of distribution restrictions and the impact on farmers, and will effectively allow distribution outside the region.
In order to prevent the spread of the virus, we will thoroughly dispose of food waste.
We will also work to prevent harmful rumors by calling for the safety of vaccinated pigs.
The draft amendments to the guidelines were compiled at a meeting of the expert panel held on the same day and confirmed at a meeting of the Anti-epidemic Headquarters.
In the future, opinions will be made to prefectures and public comments until October 7th, and new epidemic prevention guidelines will be implemented.
