How to prevent dementia and keep it to the degree of "forgetting"?
Interview / Text / Yo Watanabe (Yoshi Watanabe)
Major pharmaceutical companies and university hospitals are struggling with research and development, and drugs for dementia are frustrated.
However, the relationship between dementia and lifestyle habits is being elucidated, and it has become clear that it is possible to keep it to a very mild illness and forgetfulness.
We spoke to Professor Shunsuke Otsuki of the Stroke Center at Kinki University Hospital.
Dementia will not disappear
Dementia prevention or treatment is expected, but what is the current situation?
Otsuki From mild to severe, regardless of the degree of difference, everyone may have dementia as they age.
However, it is believed that it will still take more than 20 years for new dementia drugs to be developed.
Donepegil, a drug that is often used in Japan, is already out of insurance coverage in some countries overseas, and we can not expect a noticeable cure effect.
On the other hand, as deaths from infectious diseases and accidents have decreased, and cancer deaths have also decreased due to remarkable advances in treatment such as anticancer drugs, and people can live longer.
As a result, the number of dementia patients is increasing.
It is not something that can be solved by the person or a family, but it is necessary to create an environment where society as a whole can live with peace of mind in the community.
How to keep it to the extent of "forgetting things"
Are there people who are prone to dementia and people who are difficult to become?
Otsuki Even if it is inevitable that you will have dementia, there is a possibility that you can suppress the symptoms as much as possible and keep it to the extent that you forget.
Dementia is considered to be one of the lifestyle diseases, and there is a tendency for people who are prone to becoming.
First of all, people with metabolic syndrome tend to be more prone to dementia.
Dementia is considered a lifestyle disease.
It is a combination of obesity, high blood pressure, diabetes mellitus and hypercholesterolemia.
It also affects the lack of economic power.
For example, there are regions in the United States that distribute food vouchers to the poor, but the food you can get with food tickets are frozen hamburgers, pizzas and chicken that can be stored.
It can be used by people who can't use gas or electricity, and they can live in an environment where they can't cook in the first place.
Then, it becomes a diet with less vegetables and protein, and it becomes a life that is biased toward lipids and carbohydrates.
Eventually, you will become poor, but you will become obese, and the only thing you can do is to watch TV, and your body will be disabled.
A similar situation can be found in Japan.
In addition, people who do not think or work tend to have dementia.
In other words, in order to prevent dementia, it is necessary to read books and think about things on a daily basis, which is not metabolic.
